<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,289,2009]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,289,315]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species (
<figureCitation box="[427,558,290,316]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–48" captionStartId="31.[151,264,1907,1931]" captionTargetBox="[170,1418,181,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-16@31.[170,1418,181,1883]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURES 40–48. Habitus images of Cyrtocapsus spp. 40, 41, C. metafemoratus. 40, male, dorsal aspect. 41, holotype female, dorsal aspect. 42, 43, C. nordestinus. 42, male, dorsal aspect. 43, male, lateral aspect. 44, 45, C. pallipes. 44, male, dorsal aspect. 45, female, dorsal aspect. 46, 47, C. paraensis, holotype female (of C. bolivianus). 46, dorsal aspect. 47, lateral aspect. 48, C. paraguaiensis, holotype female, dorsal aspect." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6646375" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6646375/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Figs. 40, 41</figureCitation>
) is readily distinguished by the yellowish- to brownish-orange head, sometimes with fuscous marks on the vertex and frons; the fuscous to dark brown pronotum, with a broad pale brownish-orange area along posterior margin; the dark brown hemelytron, with the embolium and apex of the corium pale yellowish orange; and the pale yellow to yellowish-white legs, with only the apical third of the hind femur and the base of the hind tibia fuscous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,289,2009]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
It is superficially similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[508,603,470,496]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Cyrtocapus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fiuzai">
<emphasis box="[508,603,470,496]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">C. fiuzai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[618,752,470,497]" captionStart="FIGURES 18–28" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1895,1919]" captionTargetBox="[176,1412,181,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-32@14.[176,1412,181,1871]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 18–28. Habitus images of Cyrtocapsus spp. 18, 19, C. discalis, holotype male. 18, dorsal aspect. 19, lateral aspect. 20–22, C. elutipes. 20, male, dorsal aspect. 21, female, dorsal aspect. 22, female, lateral aspect. 23, 24, C. femoralis, lectotype male. 23, dorsal aspect. 24, lateral aspect. 25, 26, C. fiuzai. 25, male, dorsal aspect. 26, female, dorsal aspect. 27, 28, C. glabratus, holotype male. 27, dorsal aspect. 28, lateral aspect." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6646371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6646371/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Figs. 25, 26</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reuter" authorityYear="1909" box="[814,978,470,496]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Cyrtocapsus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intermedius">
<emphasis box="[814,978,470,496]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">C. intermedius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[994,1075,470,496]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–39" captionStartId="27.[151,264,1907,1931]" captionTargetBox="[170,1417,181,1881]" captionTargetId="figure-16@27.[170,1418,181,1883]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 29–39. Habitus images of Cyrtocapsus spp. 29, 30, C. grenadensis. 29, male, dorsal aspect. 30, female, dorsal aspect. 31, C. guianus, holotype female, dorsal aspect. 32, 33, C. haitianus. 32, male dorsal aspect. 33, female, dorsal aspect. 34, C. intermedius, female, dorsal aspect. 35, 36, C. lazelli. 35, male, dorsal aspect. 36, female, dorsal aspect. 37, 38, C. marginatus. 37, lectotype male, dorsal aspect. 38, paralectotype female, dorsal aspect. 39, C. mesoamericanus, holotype male, dorsal aspect." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6646373" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6646373/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
) in the overall dark brown color with the posterior margin of the pronotum and embolium paler yellow to brownish orange but differs from these two species in having the apical third of the hind femur and base of the hind tibial fuscous rather than uniformly pale yellowish white.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,289,2009]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<taxonomicName box="[199,515,614,640]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Cyrtocapsus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metafemoratus">
<emphasis box="[199,515,614,640]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Cyrtocapsus metafemoratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[739,881,614,640]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Cyrtocapsus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="femoralis">
<emphasis box="[739,881,614,640]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">C. femoralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[900,984,614,640]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–39" captionStartId="27.[151,264,1907,1931]" captionTargetBox="[170,1417,181,1881]" captionTargetId="figure-16@27.[170,1418,181,1883]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 29–39. Habitus images of Cyrtocapsus spp. 29, 30, C. grenadensis. 29, male, dorsal aspect. 30, female, dorsal aspect. 31, C. guianus, holotype female, dorsal aspect. 32, 33, C. haitianus. 32, male dorsal aspect. 33, female, dorsal aspect. 34, C. intermedius, female, dorsal aspect. 35, 36, C. lazelli. 35, male, dorsal aspect. 36, female, dorsal aspect. 37, 38, C. marginatus. 37, lectotype male, dorsal aspect. 38, paralectotype female, dorsal aspect. 39, C. mesoamericanus, holotype male, dorsal aspect." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6646373" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6646373/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
) in body coloration and parameres but differs in having all coxae pale yellowish white, the hind femur apically fuscous, and a slightly more stout right paramere lacking lateral indentations, whereas 
<taxonomicName box="[677,816,686,712]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Cyrtocapsus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="femoralis">
<emphasis box="[677,816,686,712]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">C. femoralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has brown hind coxae, all femora apically fuscous, and the right paramere is distinctly indented laterally. Despite the similarities, several relatively long series indicate the coxal and femoral marking consistently distinguish these two species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
